{{Quote|I doubt I'll ever win any prestigious literary awards for my work, but I'm okay with that.|Drew Karpyshyn|<ref name="DrewSWTOR">{{WebCite|url=http://www.drewkarpyshyn.com/news.htm|text=February 24: Drew Karpyshyn joins SWTOR team|archivedate=20200614020014}}</ref>}}
'''Drew Karpyshyn'''<ref name="Name">Pronounced Kar-pish-in</ref> is a Canadian video-game designer, video-game writer, and author. After working at a credit union for some time, he became a game developer. He joined [[BioWare]] and became the senior writer and one of the core game designers on the critically acclaimed game ''[[Star Wars: Knights of the Old Republic]]''.

This ''Star Wars'' connection gave him the opportunity to write the novels ''[[Darth Bane: Path of Destruction]]'', ''[[Darth Bane: Rule of Two]]'', and ''[[Darth Bane: Dynasty of Evil]]'', his first hardcovers.

He worked as a writer on the game ''[[Star Wars: The Old Republic]]''<ref name="DrewSWTOR" /> and wrote two novels set in the same era, ''[[The Old Republic: Revan]]'' and ''[[The Old Republic: Annihilation]]''. Karpyshyn left BioWare in [[February]] [[2012]] to work on other projects. He returned to the company in [[September]] [[2015]] only to leave again in [[March]] [[2018]].

==Biography==
===Early life===
As a child, he was a big fan of ''[[Star Wars]]''. Between the ages of 8 and 12, Karpyshyn dressed up as a [[Jawa/Legends|Jawa]] for Halloween. When his friend told him [[Anakin Skywalker|Darth Vader]] was [[Luke Skywalker]]'s father, he was wholly unconvinced.<ref name="Blog4">{{Blog|DrewK|4|Confessions of a fan-boy}}</ref>

===Career===
On [[July 15]], [[2003]], ''[[Star Wars: Knights of the Old Republic]]'' was released on the [[Wikipedia:Xbox|Xbox]]. Karpyshyn was the lead writer and one of seven members of the core design team. Development of the game began around [[December]] of [[2000]], and it was unveiled at the [[2001]] [[Wikipedia:Electronic Entertainment Expo|Electronic Entertainment Expo]].<ref name="E32001">{{GameSpot|url=pc/rpg/starwarsknightsoftor/news.html?sid=2762052|text=E3 2001: LucasArts unveils BioWare RPG|author=Ajami, Amer|date=2001-05-18|nobackup=1}}</ref> ''Knights of the Old Republic'' received a great deal of praise and awards.<ref name="awards">{{WebCite|url=http://www.bioware.com/games/knights_old_republic/awards|text=Star Wars: Knights of the Old Republic Awards|archivedate=20011230090020}}</ref> According to Karpyshyn, the game "let me get my foot in the door with LucasArts," eventually leading to his career as a ''Star Wars'' novelist.<ref name="sitegames">{{WebCite|url=http://www.drewkarpyshyn.com/games.htm|text=Drew Karpyshyn Creative Works: Games|author=Karpyshyn, Drew|archivedate=20200329101534}}</ref>

More significantly, he published his first ''Star Wars'' novel, ''[[Darth Bane: Path of Destruction]]''. It was also his first hardcover book. In 2007, he quickly wrote a sequel, ''[[Darth Bane: Rule of Two]]'', and later published the third book in the series, ''[[Darth Bane: Dynasty of Evil]]''. He also saw the release of the acclaimed ''Mass Effect'' game.

